1. Introduction\par
1.1 Background\par
The average American moves about eleven times in their lifetime. This brings us to the\par
question: Do people move until they find a place to settle down where they truly feel happy,\par
or do our wants and needs change over time, prompting us to eventually leave a town we\par
once called home for a new area that will bring us satisfaction? Or, do we too often move to\par
a new area without knowing exactly what we\rquote re getting into, forcing us to turn tail and run at\par
the first sign of discomfort?\par
To minimize the chances of this happening, we should always do proper research when\par
planning our next move in life. Consider the following factors when picking a new place to\par
live so you don\rquote t end up wasting your valuable time and money making a move you\rquote ll end\par
up regretting. Safety is a top concern when moving to a new area. If you don\rquote t feel safe in\par
your own home, you\rquote re not going to be able to enjoy living there.\par
\par
\par
1.2 Problem\par
The crime statistics dataset of London found on Kaggle has crimes in each Boroughs of\par
London from 2008 to 2016. The year 2016 being the latest we will be considering the data\par
of that year which is actually old information as of now. The crime rates in each borough\par
may have changed over time.\par
This project aims to select the safest borough in London based on the total crimes, explore\par
the neighborhoods of that borough to find the 10 most common venues in each\par
neighborhood and finally cluster the neighborhoods using k-mean clustering.\par
\par
\par
1.3 Interest\par
Expats who are considering to relocate to London will be interested to identify the safest\par
borough in London and explore its neighborhoods and common venues around each\par
neighborhood.\par
\par
