3.2 Modelling\par
Using the final dataset containing the neighborhoods in Kingston upon Thames along with\par
the latitude and longitude, we can find all the venues within a 500 meter radius of each\par
neighborhood by connecting to the Foursquare API. This returns a json file containing all\par
the venues in each neighborhood which is converted to a pandas dataframe. This data\par
frame contains all the venues along with their coordinates and category (see fig 3.2.1).\par
Fig 3.2.1 Venue details of each Neighborhood\par
One hot encoding is done on the venues data. (One hot encoding is a process by which\par
categorical variables are converted into a form that could be provided to ML algorithms to\par
do a better job in prediction). The Venues data is then grouped by the Neighborhood and\par
the mean of the venues are calculated, finally the 10 common venues are calculated for\par
each of the neighborhoods.\par
To help people find similar neighborhoods in the safest borough we will be clustering similar\par
neighborhoods using K - means clustering which is a form of unsupervised machine\par
learning algorithm that clusters data based on predefined cluster size. We will use a cluster\par
size of 5 for this project that will cluster the 15 neighborhoods into 5 clusters. The reason to\par
conduct a K- means clustering is to cluster neighborhoods with similar venues together so\par
that people can shortlist the area of their interests based on the venues/amenities around\par
each neighborhood.\par
